<!-- ENGINEERING CANDOR -->
<section class="t8-paper2">
  <div style="max-width:1536px;margin:0 auto;padding:3rem 1.5rem;">
    <div class="t8-candor" style="max-width:56rem;">
      <p class="t8-candor-ey" style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">— ENGINEERING CANDOR · LAB VS. FIELD</p>
      <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Where the spec-sheet number and the field number diverge.</h3>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:0.75rem;opacity:0.9;">L70 is calculated against TM-21 lab data at 35°C ambient. Real-world commercial installs run cooler (open-troffer ambient typically 28–32°C) which extends practical service life by 15–20% — but warehouse high-bay applications and recessed downlights can run 5–10°C hotter, reducing it. The published L70 number is the conservative TM-21 calculation, not the optimistic best-case.</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.7;opacity:0.9;">Inrush current at install can spike higher than the typical 30A peak when 20+ Workhorse T8s share a single 20A circuit and energize together — circuit re-balancing or staggered control may be needed. We document this in the install guide because the spec sheet alone won't catch it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

